author: @RabeezRiaz
text: The text printed at 7:53 was the return value of set_xticklabels(), you can suppress it by using a semicolon at the end of that line (very un-pythhonic, I know :D) Also you can remove the plt.show() call by running `%matplotlib inline` in a cell somewhere before your plots.

author: @RabeezRiaz
text: Hey Harrison. You could use the plt.subplots() function to generate the figure and the axes together, it's nrows and ncols arguments feel more easy to use in my experience than the 111/221 thing of add_subplots()
